abstract = {In today's world, in the era of globalization, computerization, and the development of informative society, cities face many problems and growth challenges. Meeting those demands requires, among other things, the adoption of a relevant conception of further development and also the governance model. Over the last years, what has become particularly popular was the smart city governance conception with the significant role of residents together with their formal and informal knowledge, skills, and creativity in decision-making process. In this chapter, it has been assumed that the implementation of smart city governance is possible thanks to the adoption of appropriate development policies (to increase public participation, improve access to information-communication technologies and the open data policy), which are conducive to the development of platforms intended for stimulating bottom-up participatory. Attention is paid mainly to platforms that serve the phenomena called coproduction (including geoparticipation, crowdsourcing, crowdfunding, hackathons, Living Labs, gamification) and cocreation of value (e.g., urban hacktivism and BarCamps).}
